    slug: "rozon-kay-masail",
    description: `Rozon Kay Masail (Issues Related to Fasting) is a comprehensive Urdu-language book that addresses the jurisprudential rulings (masail) related to fasting (Sawm) in Islam. As one of the five pillars of Islam, fasting during the month of Ramadan is an obligatory act of worship for every adult, sane, and healthy Muslim. Beyond Ramadan, there are various categories of voluntary fasting and specific situations that raise questions about the validity and rules of fasting. This book systematically covers all these issues according to the Hanafi school of jurisprudence while also mentioning relevant opinions from other schools where applicable.

The book begins with the foundational rulings of fasting: who is obligated to fast, who is exempt (the sick, the traveler, the elderly, pregnant and nursing women, children, and the mentally incapacitated), and what constitutes the intention (niyyah) required for a valid fast. The definition of a fast and its essential components are explained with reference to the Quranic command to fast and the detailed hadith narrations in which the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) explained the rules of fasting to his companions.

A major section of the book is devoted to things that invalidate the fast (mufsidat-e-sawm). Each invalidator is discussed with the conditions under which it breaks the fast and whether expiation (kaffarah), makeup fasting (qada), or both are required. The book covers eating and drinking deliberately, intentional vomiting, menstruation and post-natal bleeding, the use of certain medications, and other specific scenarios. Crucially, the book distinguishes between acts that invalidate the fast entirely and those that are makruh (disliked) but do not break it, providing clarity on common misconceptions that lead some Muslims to unnecessarily abandon their fasts out of doubt.

The rulings regarding Sehri (pre-dawn meal) and Iftar (breaking the fast) are given detailed treatment, including the exact timing of Sehri, the preferred time to break the fast, and the supplications recommended at both times. The book addresses the permissibility and conditions of using inhalers, eye drops, ear drops, and other medical treatments during fasting — questions that are particularly relevant for contemporary Muslims managing chronic health conditions during Ramadan.

Special situations receive thorough coverage: fasting while traveling, fasting for the elderly who are unable to fast, the rules of fidyah (compensation by feeding the poor), the rules of kaffarah (expiation for deliberately breaking a fast), the fasts of Ramadan for women experiencing irregular cycles, and the combined fasts (qada fasts) that must be made up after Ramadan. The book also covers voluntary fasts — the six fasts of Shawwal, fasting on Mondays and Thursdays, the fasts of Ayyam al-Bidh (the middle three days of the lunar month), the fast of Arafah, the fast of Ashura, and the fast of Dawud (every other day).

Throughout the book, the author provides answers to common questions that arise in practice, making this a practical reference that Muslims can consult whenever they face uncertainty about their fast. The clear and systematic presentation, combined with the authoritative source references, makes Rozon Kay Masail an essential resource for every Muslim household, particularly during the month of Ramadan.`,
    metaDescription: "Rozon Kay Masail is a comprehensive Urdu guide on fasting jurisprudence. Covers invalidators, exemptions, medical issues, and expiation rulings."
